Domain Description: This is the subject area version of the Member domain. A member is an insured individual with associated health insurance data, such as claims, eligibility, or authorization. A member obtains insurance coverage through a health plan for one or more products and associated benefits and services. A member can also have multiple coverage services through different contracted insurance and employer group offerings. All coverage is evaluated through a coordination of benefits model. A member is either the primary subscriber (holds the insurance relationship) or a dependent through a member subscriber.

This is a unique identifier
This is the event in a member's life that allows them to participate in a special enrollment period. Examples include: change in family status, change in employment status, and change in coverage.
This code is associated with the event. Examples include: 1C for change in family status, 1D for change in employment status, and 1Q for change in family member's eligibility.
This is the transaction code for the type of transaction that occurred due to the event. Examples include deletion, accretion, and group accretion.
This is the effective date for the specified transaction.
This is the code associated with the insurance plan for the affected coverage.
This is the plan benefit package associated with the event.
This is the state in which the event occurred.
This is the county in which the event occurred.
This is the start date of the special enrollment period due the event. This is often the date of the qualifying event.
This is the end date of the special enrollment period due the event. This is often 30, 60, or 90 days after the qualifying event.
This is the user-defined reason for creating this transaction record.

A member obtains insurance coverage through a health plan for one or more products and associated benefits and services. A member can also have multiple coverage services through different contracted insurance and employer group offerings. All coverage is evaluated through a coordination of benefits model. A member is either the primary subscriber (holds the insurance relationship) or a dependent through a member subscriber.

Description: A logical delete (sometimes referred to as a soft delete) is a delete that doesn't actually delete the relevant data but instead marks the data as deleted. If true, this indicates that this record was marked as deleted in the source, but still remains in the Abacus Domain Model, which has an append-only model. A record marked as voided or inactive in the source is ingested into the domain model with this field set to true.
